500|$|Minton abhorred racial {{segregation}} {{and provided a}} solid vote to strike down the school segregation practices at issue in 1954's landmark case of Brown v. Board of Education; it was among the few decisions in which he sided against the government. According to William Radcliff, the majority opinion authored by Minton in the 1953 case Barrows v. Jackson was his most skillfully <b>written</b> <b>opinion.</b> He framed the complex question of the case as: [...] "Can a racially restrictive covenant be enforced at law by a suit for damages against a co-covenantor who allegedly broke the covenant?" [...] The Court decided the answer in the negative.|$|E
