25|$|Until 1788, {{the judges}} did not render <b>written</b> <b>opinions</b> or give {{reasons for their}} decisions. Pendleton felt that the policy of no <b>written</b> <b>opinions</b> {{preserved}} a semblance of unity for the court and lent more credence to their decisions. Thomas Jefferson disagreed and began recording {{the decisions of the}} court in his reports. The court convened on the tenth day of April and met for twenty-four days unless they were able to complete their business sooner.|$|R
